```python
            print("****Alignment****")
            print("sequence: %s" % alignment.title)
            print("length: %i" % alignment.length)
            print("e value: %f" % hsp.expect)
            print(hsp.query[0:75] + "...")
            print(hsp.match[0:75] + "...")
            print(hsp.sbjct[0:75] + "...")
```

```python
E_VALUE_THRESH = 0.1
```

```python
for alignment in b_record.alignments:

            print("****Alignment****")
            print("sequence: %s" % alignment.title)
            print("length: %i" % alignment.length)
            print("e value: %f" % hsp.expect)
            print(hsp.query[0:75] + "...")
            print(hsp.match[0:75] + "...")
            print(hsp.sbjct[0:75] + "...")
```

```python
# Using the method of Harris Corner Detection

gray = np.float32(gray_flat_chess)
dst = cv2.cornerHarris(src = gray, blockSize = 2, ksize = 3, k = 0.04)
```

```python
# Taking some other paths to analyze; it is 75 which is close to above half of the 127 parameters we had set


med_value = np.median(img)
med_value
```




    75.0




```python
# Changing the thresholds; the 0 and 0.7 is 0 or 70% of or median value to which is lower; the 255 and 1.3 is of the median value to which is higher
# The picture looks the same to me, but it the demonstration there is a different img being used so maybe it is just my img that does not really dhow any difference here

lower = int(max(0, 0.7*med_value))
upper = int(max(255, 1.3*med_value))

edges = cv2.Canny(image = img, threshold1 = lower, threshold2 = upper)
plt.imshow(edges)
```

# Feature Matching Detection

```python
# Starting like how we started with the other OpenCV stuff

import cv2
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
```


```python
# Setting up how we are going to display the images we are importing

def display(img, cmap = "gray"):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12, 10))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ax.imshow(img, cmap = 'gray')
```


```python
# Uploading the Apple_Jacks photo that was obtained from the interweb

apple_jacks = cv2.imread("Apple_Jacks.png", 0)
display(apple_jacks)
```


![png](output_2_0.png)



```python
# Uploading the Cereals photo that was obtained from the interweb

cereals = cv2.imread("Cereal.jpg", 0)
display(cereals)
```


![png](output_3_0.png)



```python
# Trying out Brute Force Matching; orb is a way to find certain descriptions in the imgs displayed

orb = cv2.ORB_create()

kp1,des1 = orb.detectAndCompute(apple_jacks, mask = None)
kp2,des2 = orb.detectAndCompute(cereals, mask = None)
```


```python
# bf = Brute Force; Matching the key points like des1 and des2

bf = cv2.BFMatcher(cv2.NORM_HAMMING, crossCheck = True)
matches = bf.match(des1, des2)
```


```python
# We want good matches that closely correlate

matches = sorted(matches, key = lambda x:x.distance)
```


```python
# So this will compare the two images to one another and point out the key similarities between the two to see if there are a distinct match 

apple_jacks_matches = cv2.drawMatches(apple_jacks, kp1, cereals, kp2, matches[:25], None, flags = 2)
```


```python
display(apple_jacks_matches)
```


![png](output_8_0.png)



```python
# Had to go to the terminal and uninstall both opencv and opencv-contrib and reinstall opencv-contrib for things to work

sift = cv2.SIFT_create()
```


```python
# Kinda like using the orb technique again but with sift

kp1, des1 = sift.detectAndCompute(apple_jacks, mask = None)
kp2, des2 = sift.detectAndCompute(cereals, mask = None)
```


```python
# using Brute Force again

bf = cv2.BFMatcher()
matches = bf.knnMatch(des1, des2, k = 2)
```


```python
# Applying a ratio to it, which will allow the system to say that if it goes beyond the ratio that it is not a match

good = []

for match1, match2 in matches:
    if match1.distance < 0.75*match2.distance:
        good.append([match1])
```


```python
# Printing out the numeral account of the total number of matches and good matches we have; we have 45 good matches

print('Length of total matches:', len(matches))
print('Length of good matches:', len(good))
```

    Length of total matches: 1335
    Length of good matches: 45



```python
# This helps narrow down the pick-and-point process a lot better

sift_matches = cv2.drawMatchesKnn(apple_jacks, kp1, cereals, kp2, good, None, flags = 2)
display(sift_matches)
```


![png](output_14_0.png)



```python
# Using Flann Base Matching; faster than sift, not as good, but find general matches
# Ran this before

sift = cv2.SIFT_create()

kp1, des1 = sift.detectAndCompute(apple_jacks, mask = None)
kp2, des2 = sift.detectAndCompute(cereals, mask = None)
```


```python
flann_index_KDtree = 0
index_params = dict(algorithm=flann_index_KDtree, trees = 5)
search_params = dict(checks=50)
```


```python
# We are making features in both the cereals and apple-jacks images to find similarities
# We want clusters

flann = cv2.FlannBasedMatcher(index_params, search_params)

matches = flann.knnMatch(des1, des2, k =2)

good = []

for match1, match2 in matches:
    if match1.distance < 0.75*match2.distance:
        good.append([match1])
```


```python
# Displaying those matches

flann_matches = cv2.drawMatchesKnn(apple_jacks, kp1, cereals, kp2, good, None, flags = 0)
display(flann_matches)
```


![png](output_18_0.png)



```python
# Adding a mask to our flann_matches

sift = cv2.SIFT_create()

kp1, des1 = sift.detectAndCompute(apple_jacks, mask = None)
kp2, des2 = sift.detectAndCompute(cereals, mask = None)
```


```python
flann_index_KDtree = 0
index_params = dict(algorithm=flann_index_KDtree, trees = 5)
search_params = dict(checks=50)
```


```python
# using the same code but changing the parameters of the code

flann = cv2.FlannBasedMatcher(index_params, search_params)

matches = flann.knnMatch(des1, des2, k =2)
```


```python
matchesMask = [[0,0] for i in range(len(matches))]
```


```python
# What we are doing here is that we are showing all of the features that we wanted to identify

for i, (match1, match2) in enumerate(matches):
    if match1.distance < 0.75*match2.distance:
        matchesMask[i] = [1,0]
        
draw_params = dict(matchColor = (0,255,0),
                   singlePointColor = (255,0,0), 
                   matchesMask = matchesMask,
                   flags = 0)
```


```python
# Displaying those features that we wanted to see and changed the line color to make it easier to follow

flann_matches = cv2.drawMatchesKnn(apple_jacks, kp1, cereals, kp2, matches, None, **draw_params)

display(flann_matches)
```

```python
# Saved our methods into variables

methods = ['cv2.TM_CCOEFF', 'cv2.TM_CCOEFF_NORMED', 'cv2.TM_CCORR', 'cv2.TM_CCORR_NORMED', 'cv2.TM_SQDIFF', 'cv2.TM_SQDIFF_NORMED']
```


```python
# Going to match the test and full picture with one another and circle to which is matched

for m in methods:
    
    test_copy = test.copy()
    method = eval(m)
    
    res = cv2.matchTemplate(test_copy, full, method)
    
    min_val, max_val, min_loc, max_loc = cv2.minMaxLoc(res)
    
    if method in [cv2. TM_SQDIFF, cv2.TM_SQDIFF_NORMED]:
        top_left = min_loc
    else:
        top_left = max_loc
        
# We are taking whatever we are adding to the top left of our box and adding the width and the height 

    height, width, channels = full.shape
    bottom_right = (top_left[0] + width, top_left[1] + height)
    
    cv2.rectangle(test_copy, top_left, bottom_right, (255,0,0),10)
    
    plt.subplot(121)
    plt.imshow(res)
    plt.title("Heatmap of template matching")
    plt.subplot(122)
    plt.imshow(test_copy)
    plt.title('Detection of template')
    
    plt.suptitle(m)

# So I messed up somewhere and the system is not showing any similarity of the two images with the heatmapping, but they are def the same type of flower.   
    
    plt.show()
```
